    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate focusing on high-ceiling matchups against soft-throwing rotations. Our strongest play is **Vinnie Pasquantino** (76.21), whose value is bolstered by a favorable matchup against Tanner Bibee and a significant dynamic platoon advantage. He joins **Seiya Suzuki** (71.23) and **Josh Naylor** (70.82) as our daily anchors; **Seiya Suzuki** specifically benefits from an elite 19% SP skill adjustment against Chase Petty, while **Josh Naylor** leverages a strong batting order placement and a favorable encounter with JR Ritchie. Even with the lineup uncertainty, **Mickey Moniak** (69.69) remains a high-floor start due to the park factors, though we must keep a watchful eye on the 34% rain risk threatening his appearance.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved choosing between **Cole Young** and the surging **Trevor Story**. While **Cole Young** (49.60) narrowly secured the final starting middle-infield spot, he only edged out **Trevor Story** (44.70) because the latter is running into a buzzsaw in Tarik Skubal. The optimizer prioritized the favorable matchup against JR Ritchie for our starters, effectively neutralizing the upside **Trevor Story** provides. Elsewhere, **Jose Caballero** (47.55) retains a roster spot primarily for his disruptive potential on the basepaths; despite the poor platoon grade against Shane Baz, his ability to capitalize on slow deliveries keeps him in the mix as our primary SB engine. We are keeping **Kyle Karros** (52.82) active despite the rain risk, banking on his significant park-factor boost to outweigh the marginal weather concerns.",
